<!-- ════ QUICK SUMMARY ════ -->
<section id="at-glance" class="section section--place" style="background:#F8F4EC;padding:var(--section-pad)">
 <div class="container">
  <div class="summary-callout">
   <h2>At a Glance</h2>
   <p>Public beautification is not luxury — it is signal. A well-maintained streetscape with trees, fountains, and benches tells residents and visitors that a city invests in itself. These improvements cost a fraction of major infrastructure projects but generate psychological and economic returns disproportionate to their investment. Vision 2040's beautification strategy focuses on high-visibility corridors and gathering spaces that create a perceptual shift in how people experience El Dorado.</p>

   <div class="summary-grid">
    <div class="summary-item">
     <h4>💡 Beautification Strategy</h4>
     <ul>
      <li>Central Avenue Streetscape Redesign</li>
      <li>Downtown fountain features & plaza</li>
      <li>Public bench program (75 new benches)</li>
      <li>Street tree planting (200+ trees)</li>
      <li>Mural & public art program</li>
      <li>Gateway entry corridor improvements</li>
      <li>Neighborhood sign standards</li>
      <li>Lighting improvements (downtown & major roads)</li>
     </ul>
    </div>

    <div class="summary-item">
     <h4>🌳 Landscaping & Trees</h4>
     <ul>
      <li>Street tree program: 200+ native/adapted species</li>
      <li>Species selection: drought-tolerant, long-lived</li>
      <li>Structural soil cells (reduces compaction)</li>
      <li>Enhanced irrigation for establishment (3–5 years)</li>
      <li>15-year maintenance covenant</li>
      <li>Property owner partnership model</li>
      <li>Est. 12–15 ft canopy coverage by 2035</li>
     </ul>
    </div>

    <div class="summary-item">
     <h4>💧 Water Features & Plazas</h4>
     <ul>
      <li>Central Plaza fountain (downtown centerpiece)</li>
      <li>Seasonal splash pad (young children)</li>
      <li>Winter ice skating feature</li>
      <li>Walnut River overlook with seating</li>
      <li>El Dorado Lake scenic viewpoints (3 locations)</li>
      <li>Native plantings around water features</li>
      <li>Stormwater management integration</li>
     </ul>
    </div>

    <div class="summary-item">
     <h4>🎨 Public Art & Wayfinding</h4>
     <ul>
      <li>5+ large-format public art installations</li>
      <li>Commissioned murals from Kansas artists</li>
      <li>Wayfinding signage (downtown historic sites)</li>
      <li>Gateway entry monuments (US-54 & US-77)</li>
      <li>"Instagrammable" public art destinations</li>
      <li>Alley activation with curated art</li>
      <li>Lighting on major public artworks</li>
     </ul>
    </div>
   </div>
  </div>

  <!-- ════ DATA SOURCES ════ -->
  <div class="data-sources-box">
   <h3>📚 Data Sources</h3>
   <p>This page incorporates data from the following sources:</p>
   <ul class="sources-list">
    <li><strong>DataUSA:</strong> <em>El Dorado, KS profile</em> — Population density, neighborhood demographics. <a href="https://datausa.io/profile/geo/el-dorado-ks/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">datausa.io/profile/geo/el-dorado-ks/</a></li>
    <li><strong>Kansas Health Matters:</strong> <em>Environmental Health Indicators</em> — Green space access, walkability. <a href="https://www.kansashealthmatters.org/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">kansashealthmatters.org</a></li>
    <li><strong>ASLA (American Society of Landscape Architects):</strong> Public realm ROI, tree canopy benefits, streetscape design standards</li>
    <li><strong>Project for Public Spaces:</strong> Placemaking research, bench placement, public gathering space design</li>
    <li><strong>Trees Are Good (Texas A&M):</strong> Urban forest benefits, tree species selection, maintenance standards</li>
   </ul>
  </div>
 </div>
</section>

<!-- ════ MAIN CONTENT ════ -->
<section id="beautification-initiatives" class="section section--place" style="padding:var(--section-pad)">
 <div class="container">

  <h2 style="margin-bottom:2rem">Beautification & Public Realm Projects</h2>

  <div class="glass-card reveal">
   <span class="badge badge--sky">Complete Street · $2.8M</span>
   <div class="icon">🌳</div>
   <h3>Central Avenue Streetscape Redesign</h3>
   <p>Central Avenue gets redesigned as a complete street prioritizing pedestrians and public gathering. Key improvements:</p>
   <ul style="margin-top:1rem;margin-left:1.5rem">
    <li><strong>Widened Sidewalks:</strong> Expanded from 8 ft to 12–13 ft to accommodate trees, café seating, and pedestrian comfort</li>
    <li><strong>Street Trees:</strong> 80 new native/adapted species in structural soil cells — providing canopy shade and summer cooling</li>
    <li><strong>Period-Appropriate Lighting:</strong> Consistent historic-style street lights (oil-era design motif) from block to block</li>
    <li><strong>Decorative Crosswalks:</strong> Patterned or colored pavement at key intersections (oil-boom heritage motifs)</li>
    <li><strong>Public Benches:</strong> 20 new benches spaced every 100–150 ft for resting and people-watching</li>
    <li><strong>Stormwater Management:</strong> Bioswales and permeable pavement reduce runoff, support tree growth</li>
   </ul>
   <p style="margin-top:1rem"><strong>Research:</strong> FHWA studies show 4-to-3 lane road diets reduce crash rates 29–47%, increase adjacent retail sales 15–25% within 3 years.</p>
  </div>

  <div class="glass-card reveal">
   <span class="badge" style="background:#4a90bf">Downtown Plazas & Water Features · $1.8M</span>
   <div class="icon">💧</div>
   <h3>Central Plaza, Fountains & Gathering Spaces</h3>
   <p>High-visibility public gathering spaces that become the social heart of downtown:</p>
   <div style="display:grid;grid-template-columns:repeat(2,1fr);gap:1.5rem;margin-top:1.5rem">
    <div>
     <h4>Central Plaza</h4>
     <ul>
      <li>Converted from underused surface parking</li>
      <li>Permanent covered market pavilion</li>
      <li>Performance stage (farmers market, concerts)</li>
      <li>Central fountain feature (evening lighting)</li>
      <li>Year-round splash pad (drained in winter)</li>
      <li>200–300 person capacity</li>
     </ul>
    </div>
    <div>
     <h4>Secondary Water Features</h4>
     <ul>
      <li>Walnut River Overlook (seating, interpretive signage)</li>
      <li>El Dorado Lake scenic viewpoints (3 locations)</li>
      <li>Winter ice skating feature (seasonal)</li>
      <li>Native plant integration (watershed education)</li>
      <li>Soft edge transitions to water</li>
      <li>Accessible viewing platforms (ADA compliant)</li>
     </ul>
    </div>
   </div>
  </div>

  <div class="glass-card reveal">
   <span class="badge" style="background:#6b8e23">Public Bench Program · $180K</span>
   <div class="icon">🪑</div>
   <h3>Public Seating — 75 New Benches</h3>
   <p>Research shows people spend more time in places with seating. Vision 2040 places 75 new benches strategically across El Dorado:</p>
   <ul style="margin-top:1rem;margin-left:1.5rem">
    <li><strong>Downtown Core (25 benches):</strong> Every 100–150 ft along Central Avenue, with backs to historic buildings</li>
    <li><strong>Park System (20 benches):</strong> At park entrances, along trails, and at scenic viewpoints</li>
    <li><strong>Lake Access (15 benches):</strong> Along the 26-mile trail at overlooks and rest stops</li>
    <li><strong>School Routes (8 benches):</strong> At crossings and rest points on K–12 walking corridors</li>
    <li><strong>Senior Centers (7 benches):</strong> Clustered near recreational facilities for elderly visitors</li>
   </ul>
   <p style="margin-top:1rem"><strong>Design Standard:</strong> Powder-coated steel or treated wood, 4–5 ft length, with and without backs. Heritage oil-era design motif where visible from Central Avenue. Cost per bench installed: $2,400–$3,600 (including foundation and design).</p>
  </div>

  <div class="glass-card reveal">
   <span class="badge" style="background:#8b5a3c">Street Tree Program · $1.2M</span>
   <div class="icon">🌳</div>
   <h3>Urban Forest Expansion — 200+ New Trees</h3>
   <p>El Dorado currently has 8–10% tree canopy coverage. Vision 2040 targets 15% canopy by 2035 through targeted planting:</p>
   <ul style="margin-top:1rem;margin-left:1.5rem">
    <li><strong>Central Avenue:</strong> 80 trees (structural soil cells, 45–60 ft mature height)</li>
    <li><strong>Neighborhood Streets:</strong> 70 trees (residential block tree canopy)</li>
    <li><strong>Park System:</strong> 35 trees (native shade, wildlife habitat)</li>
    <li><strong>Water Feature Buffers:</strong> 15 trees (riparian restoration, stormwater filtration)</li>
   </ul>
   <p style="margin-top:1rem"><strong>Species Selection:</strong> Native and adapted species (Chinkapin Oak, Hackberry, Redbud, Pawpaw) selected for drought tolerance, longevity, and wildlife benefit. Diverse age structure prevents monoculture aging-out risk.</p>
   <p style="margin-top:1rem"><strong>Benefits per Tree (30-year lifespan):</strong> $200+ in stormwater management value, $100+ in cooling energy savings, $75 in air quality improvement, $50+ in property value increase per adjacent property. Total: $500+ benefit per tree over 30 years.</p>
  </div>

  <div class="glass-card reveal">
   <span class="badge" style="background:#c44536">Public Art Program · $650K</span>
   <div class="icon">🎨</div>
   <h3>Murals, Public Art & Wayfinding</h3>
   <p><strong>Five Major Public Art Installations:</strong></p>
   <ul style="margin-top:1rem;margin-left:1.5rem">
    <li><strong>"El Dorado Oil Derrick" (Downtown landmark):</strong> 35-ft steel sculpture welded to oil-boom heritage, visible from multiple blocks. Cost: $120K. Location: Central Plaza southeast entrance.</li>
    <li><strong>"Neon El Dorado" Sign (Downtown Icon):</strong> Large-format neon sign on building facade, glowing at night, Instagram-famous. Cost: $45K. Location: Central Avenue &amp; Main intersection.</li>
    <li><strong>Painted Crosswalk Art (Downtown District):</strong> 4 decorative crosswalks with oil-boom era motifs and Flint Hills landscape. Cost: $60K total. Artist: Commissioned Kansas muralist.</li>
    <li><strong>Alley Activation Murals (Downtown Service Alleys):</strong> 6 large-scale murals (12 ft × 30 ft each) from local and regional Kansas artists. Cost: $12K per alley = $72K total. Program runs annually with rotating artists.</li>
    <li><strong>Gateway Entry Monuments (Highway Approaches):</strong> 2 welcoming structures at US-54 and US-77 entrances — sculptural or architectural (pilot: consider a working oil derrick design that pumps water into a small fountain). Cost: $150K each = $300K.</li>
   </ul>
   <p style="margin-top:1rem"><strong>Wayfinding Signage System:</strong> Heritage-themed directional signs linking downtown historic sites, the Kansas Oil Museum, El Dorado Lake, and community destinations. Consistent design language, bilingual English/Spanish, QR codes linking to digital content. Total: $80K.</p>
  </div>

  <div class="glass-card reveal">
   <span class="badge" style="background:#5a7a8b">Lighting Infrastructure · $890K</span>
   <div class="icon">💡</div>
   <h3>Street Lighting & Architectural Lighting</h3>
   <p><strong>Downtown Street Lighting Upgrade:</strong> Replace utility-standard lights with heritage-style period fixtures (oil-era design language) from block to block. Consistent, warm-toned illumination improves nighttime pedestrian safety and creates visual identity. LED technology reduces energy use 60–70% vs. existing fixtures. Cost: $45K per block × 8 blocks = $360K.</p>
   <p style="margin-top:1rem"><strong>Architectural Lighting on Public Buildings:</strong> Accent lighting on the Carnegie Library, Kansas Oil Museum, Petroleum Building, and Butler County Courthouse — making these heritage landmarks visible and prominent after dark. Cost: $180K.</p>
   <p style="margin-top:1rem"><strong>Public Art Lighting:</strong> Specialized lighting on major art installations (oil derrick sculpture, gateway monuments) and mural features (alleys, painted crosswalks). Cost: $150K.</p>
   <p style="margin-top:1rem"><strong>Lake & Park Lighting:</strong> Accent lighting at El Dorado Lake scenic overlooks, trail access points, and park entries. Safety-grade pathway lighting along the 26-mile circumnavigation trail (every 1/4-mile). Cost: $200K.</p>
  </div>

  <!-- ════ ROI ════ -->
  <h2 style="margin-top:3rem;margin-bottom:2rem">Beautification Return on Investment</h2>

  <div style="display:grid;grid-template-columns:repeat(3,1fr);gap:1.5rem">
   <div style="background:rgba(107,142,35,.1);border:1px solid rgba(107,142,35,.3);border-radius:var(--radius);padding:1.5rem">
    <h4>Property Values</h4>
    <p>Research shows tree-lined streets increase adjacent property values 3–15%. Downtown gateway improvement programs across comparable Kansas cities (Emporia, Salina, Hutchinson) documented average property value increases of $1,200–$3,500 per property within 3–5 years.</p>
   </div>
   <div style="background:rgba(74,144,191,.1);border:1px solid rgba(74,144,191,.3);border-radius:var(--radius);padding:1.5rem">
    <h4>Retail Sales</h4>
    <p>Streetscape improvements on main commercial corridors increase adjacent retail sales 15–25% within 3 years (FHWA research, Emporia case study). Downtown plazas and seating areas increase dwell time, leading to higher retail spending.</p>
   </div>
   <div style="background:rgba(200,100,42,.1);border:1px solid rgba(200,100,42,.3);border-radius:var(--radius);padding:1.5rem">
    <h4>Tourist Spending</h4>
    <p>Public realm quality (cleanliness, seating, landscaping, art) is the #1 rated factor in visitor satisfaction. Instagram-friendly public art & fountains generate organic social media content worth $2–5M in equivalent advertising value annually.</p>
   </div>
  </div>

 </div>
</section>

